FOODBORNE ILLNESS - INDONESIA: (BALI) FATAL, SCOMBROID SUSPECTED
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 5 Feb 2014
Source: Yahoo News, ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) report [summ., edited]
http://au.news.yahoo.com/a/21264324/bischoffs-family-told-food-poisoning-the-likely-cause-of-noelene-and-yvanas-deaths-in-bali/


A rare form of food poisoning most likely caused the deaths of a Queensland mother and daughter in Bali, their family has been told. The woman in her 50s and her teenaged daughter died in January 2014 after falling ill while on holiday. The forensic pathologists who conducted the autopsies in Brisbane have told the family that they do not suspect foul play.

A family member says it is suspected several factors combined to promote the growth of a bacterium in the fish they ate at a restaurant. "At this stage they think the cause of death is the fish... an illness called scombroid poisoning, which is a very unusual type of fish poisoning. It's not very well known," he said and added that they were told it is extremely rare for someone to die from this type of food poisoning.

Both mother and daughter suffered from mild asthma, which could have also contributed to their deaths. The family member added, "They're sort of saying it's just one in millions of chances that [this] could all come together for that to happen with 2 people at the same time." He stressed that the results remain inconclusive and authorities are awaiting final test results.

